answers.body_markdown:
here you are facing a complex case of [`min-width` constraint][1]. If you look closely you will see that you are having an overflow (if we ommit the max-width)

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .ola {
      display: flex;
      width: 110px;
      background: red;
      border:2px solid green;
    }
    .ola a {
      text-decoration: none;
    }
    .ola a:first-child {
      color: black;
      background: yellow;
    }
    .ola a:first-child img {
      height: 30px;
      width: auto;
     /* max-width: 100%;*/
    }
    .ola a:nth-child(2) {
      color: yellow;
      background: black;
      font-size: 20px;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;ola&quot;&gt;
          &lt;a href=&quot;#&quot;&gt;
            &lt;img src=&quot;https://madmin.madcoderz.com/assets/images/favicon.png&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;&gt;
          &lt;/a&gt;
          &lt;a href=&quot;#&quot;&gt;HelloWorld&lt;/a&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Your elements won&#39;t shrink because they cannot do past their content size. By adding `max-width:100%` you are changing this behavior. The precentage need to consider the parent width and the parent width depend on its content where you are applying the `max-width`. You have a kind of cycle here.

To better understand what is happening remove the `min-width` constraint and you will see that the image is overflowing the `a` element

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .ola {
      display: flex;
      width: 110px;
      background: red;
      border:2px solid green;
    }
    .ola a {
      text-decoration: none;
    }
    .ola a:first-child {
      color: black;
      background: yellow;
      min-width:0;
    }
    .ola a:first-child img {
      height: 30px;
      width: auto;
     /* max-width: 100%;*/
    }
    .ola a:nth-child(2) {
      color: yellow;
      background: black;
      font-size: 20px;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;ola&quot;&gt;
          &lt;a href=&quot;#&quot;&gt;
            &lt;img src=&quot;https://madmin.madcoderz.com/assets/images/favicon.png&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;&gt;
          &lt;/a&gt;
          &lt;a href=&quot;#&quot;&gt;HelloWorld&lt;/a&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Then if you add the `max-width` the image will logically shrink to avoid the overflow:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .ola {
      display: flex;
      width: 110px;
      background: red;
      border:2px solid green;
    }
    .ola a {
      text-decoration: none;
    }
    .ola a:first-child {
      color: black;
      background: yellow;
      min-width:0;
    }
    .ola a:first-child img {
      height: 30px;
      width: auto;
      max-width: 100%;
    }
    .ola a:nth-child(2) {
      color: yellow;
      background: black;
      font-size: 20px;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;ola&quot;&gt;
          &lt;a href=&quot;#&quot;&gt;
            &lt;img src=&quot;https://madmin.madcoderz.com/assets/images/favicon.png&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;&gt;
          &lt;/a&gt;
          &lt;a href=&quot;#&quot;&gt;HelloWorld&lt;/a&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Now the `min-width:0` become useless because the width of the image causing that constraint is now having its own constraint making it smaller enough to avoid having the intial overflow of `a` *(I know, it&#39;s also confusing for me...)*

That&#39;s why you think `max-width` is telling the browser that the image should shrink:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .ola {
      display: flex;
      width: 110px;
      background: red;
      border:2px solid green;
    }
    .ola a {
      text-decoration: none;
    }
    .ola a:first-child {
      color: black;
      background: yellow;
    }
    .ola a:first-child img {
      height: 30px;
      width: auto;
      max-width: 100%;
    }
    .ola a:nth-child(2) {
      color: yellow;
      background: black;
      font-size: 20px;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;ola&quot;&gt;
          &lt;a href=&quot;#&quot;&gt;
            &lt;img src=&quot;https://madmin.madcoderz.com/assets/images/favicon.png&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;&gt;
          &lt;/a&gt;
          &lt;a href=&quot;#&quot;&gt;HelloWorld&lt;/a&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

You will have the same result if you consider `width:100%`.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .ola {
      display: flex;
      width: 110px;
      background: red;
      border:2px solid green;
    }
    .ola a {
      text-decoration: none;
    }
    .ola a:first-child {
      color: black;
      background: yellow;
    }
    .ola a:first-child img {
      height: 30px;
      width: 100%;
    }
    .ola a:nth-child(2) {
      color: yellow;
      background: black;
      font-size: 20px;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;ola&quot;&gt;
          &lt;a href=&quot;#&quot;&gt;
            &lt;img src=&quot;https://madmin.madcoderz.com/assets/images/favicon.png&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;&gt;
          &lt;/a&gt;
          &lt;a href=&quot;#&quot;&gt;HelloWorld&lt;/a&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

To get more details about how the browser handle such cases you can refer to the specification: https://www.w3.org/TR/css-sizing-3/#percentage-sizing 

It&#39;s not trivial at all as you also need to consider flexbox algorithm and how width of replaced element is calculated. I tried to give the most simplified explanation based on what I understand from this behavior (probably not the most accurate one)

  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/q/36247140/8620333

